us|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi... A Pontificatu PII PP. IX (1846) usque ad Pontificatum Leonis PP. XIII (1903)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi...  A pontificatu Pii PP. X (1903) usque ad pontificatum Benedictii PP. XV (1922)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Cappelletti|first=Giuseppe|title=Le chiese d'Italia dalla loro origine sino ai nostri giorni|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aXFTAAAAcAAJ|volume=Volume vigesimoprimo (21)|year=1870|publisher=Antonelli|location=Venezia|language=Italian|pages=572\u2013579}}\n*Kamp, Norbert (1975). ''Kirche und Monarchie im staufischen K\u00f6nigreich Sizilien: [http://digi20.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb00042115_00001.html?prox=true&phone=true&ngram=true&seriesTitle_str=%7BKirche+und+Monarchie+im+staufischen+K%C3%B6nigreich+Sizilien%7D&hl=scan&fulltext=Kamp+Kirche+und+Monarchie&mode=simple&context=Kamp%20Kirche%20und%20Monarchie I. Prosopographische Grundlegung, Bistumer und Bischofe des Konigreichs 1194\u20131266: 3. Sizilien]'' M\u00fcnchen: Wilhelm Fink 1975, pp. 1078-1108.\n*{{cite book|author=Lanzoni, Francesco|title=Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fzlSAQAAMAAJ|year=1927|publisher=Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana|location=Rome|language=Italian|page=650}}\n*{{cite book|last=Pirro|first=Rocco|editor=Antonino Mongitore|title=Sicilia sacra disquisitionibus et notitiis illustrata|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=51YxKp8DQEEC|edition=third|volume=Tomus secundus|year=1733|publisher=haeredes P. Coppulae|pages=948-968}}\n*Rodriquez, Carlo \"Breve cenno storico sulla Chiesa Liparese,\" {{cite book|title=Giornale di scienze, letteratura ed arti per la Sicilia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3psEAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA54|volume=Volume 75|year=1841|language=Italian|pages=33\u201366}}\n*{{cite book|last1= Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Nicol\u00f2 |title=Italia sacra: sive De episcopis Italiae et insularum adjacentium, rebusque abiis praeclare gestis...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=B7ssAQAAMAAJ|volume=Tomus primus|year=1717|publisher=Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=771\u2013789}}\n\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Catholicism |portal2= Italy}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lipari, Roman Catholic Diocese of}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Sicily]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 5th century]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholic dioceses in Italy]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roman_Catholic_Diocese_of_Lipari"}
{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln", "text_new": "{{for|the diocese of the Church of England|Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Lincoln\n| latin             = Dioecesis Lincolnensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska) from SE 1.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of the Risen Christ\n| coat              = Coat of Arms of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln.svg\n| coat_size         = 175px \n| coat_alt          = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[United States]]\n| territory         = The territory that lies south of the [[Platte River]] across Southern Nebraska\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Omaha|Omaha]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 23,844<!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 613,440\n| population_as_of  = 2017\n| catholics         = 97,027\n| catholics_percent = 15.8\n| parishes          = 134\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 31\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = August 2, 1887 ({{age|1887|8|2}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska)|Cathedral of the Risen Christ]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Immaculate Conception]]\n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[James D. Conley]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Fabian Bruskewitz]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Lincoln map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ www.lincolndiocese.org]<!-- [http://example.com example.com] --> \n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Lincolnensis}}) is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[diocese]] in [[Nebraska]], [[United States]], and comprises the majority of the eastern and central portions of the state south of the [[Platte River]]. It is a [[suffragan see]] to the [[Archdiocese of Omaha]].  The [[episcopal see]] is in [[Lincoln, Nebraska]].  Bishop [[James D. Conley]] is the current ordinary of the Diocese. The [[Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska)|Cathedral of the Risen Christ]] is the [[cathedral]] [[parish]] of the diocese.\n \n==History==\n[[File:St. Mary's Catholic Church, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA.jpg|thumb|left|St. Mary's Church in Lincoln was the first cathedral]]\nThe diocese was established on August 2, 1887, by [[Pope Leo XIII]] from the territory taken from the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Omaha|Diocese of Omaha]].<ref name=historylincoln>[http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese \"Brief History of the Diocese of Lincoln\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319225817/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese |date=2015-03-19 }}  [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ Catholic Diocese of Lincoln.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319225817/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese Archived 2015-03-19] at [https://archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref><ref name=historyomaha>[http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ \"Archdiocese History\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214055440/http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ |date=2014-12-14 }}  [http://www.archomaha.org/ Archdiocese of Omaha.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20141214055440/http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ Archived 2014-12-14] at [https://web.archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bishop [[Fabian Bruskewitz]] issued a statement forbidding Catholics in the diocese to join a number of organizations, including the [[Society of St. Pius X]], [[Call to Action]], [[Planned Parenthood]], [[Catholics for a Free Choice]], the [[Hemlock Society]], and various [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] groups, under pain of excommunication.<ref name=excomm>Bruskewitz, Fabian.  [http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=2863 \"Statement of Bishop Bruskewitz Excommunicating Certain Groups\".]  Reproduced at [http://www.catholicculture.org/index.cfm CatholicCulture.org.]  1996-03-19.  Retrieved 2013-04-12.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the Diocese rejected the proposed undertaking of an audit by the National Review Board of the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] - which would have examined whether the Diocese had effectively implemented national guidelines on [[sexual abuse|sex-abuse]] programs<ref name=\"ewers\">[http://www.cwnews.com/news/viewstory.cfm?recnum=43317 \"Bishop Bruskewitz shoots back at National Review Board\",]''Catholic World News'', April 2, 2006.</ref> In June 2014, the chairman of the U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops' National Review Board for the protection of children reported that the Lincoln diocese was the only one in the United States that had yet to comply with the USCCB's charter requiring every diocese to submit its procedures for the protection of children to the Review Board for an audit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roewe|first1=Brian|title=Bishops talk sex abuse complacency, not accountability at annual meeting |url=http://ncronline.org/news/accountability/bishops-talk-sex-abuse-complacency-not-accountability-annual-meeting |accessdate=2015-05-04|work=National Catholic Reporter|date=2014-06-12}}</ref> According to a 2015 statement by Conley, the Lincoln Diocese has complied with all church and civil laws on child-abuse reporting and child protection. He stated that the audit process had been improved and that the diocese would now therefore participate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Kevin J |title=For Diocese of Lincoln, Audit Will Strengthen Its Effective Child-Protection |url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/for-diocese-of-lincoln-audit-will-strengthen-its-effective-child-protection/ |date=September 11, 2015 |publisher=National Catholic Register |access-date=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Diocese of Lincoln was the only diocese in the United States that does not allow female altar servers, after the only other holdout ended its prohibition on females in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neb. diocese is lone U.S. holdout on allowing altar girls |url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/religion/2006-03-22-altar-girls_x.htm |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109074610/https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/religion/2006-03-22-altar-girls_x.htm |archivedate=9 November 2017| url-status=live|date=22 March 2006}}</ref> However, it was joined by a church in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|Diocese of Phoenix]] in August 2011, when it was announced that girls would no longer be allowed to altar serve.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clancy |first1=Michael |title=Phoenix diocese cathedral won't allow girl altar servers |url=http://archive.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/local/articles/20110821phoenix-catholic-diocese-girl-servers.html#ixzz2HBvJANlK |website=The Arizona Republic |publisher=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.fo/NA111 |archivedate=2 November 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics and statistics<ref>{{cite web |title=Statistics |url=https://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/about-the-diocese/statistics |website=www.lincolndiocese.org}}</ref>==\n*Diocese patron: [[Immaculate Conception]]\n*Priests: 164\n*Deacons: 1 permanent; 2 transitional\n*Seminarians: 39\n*[[Catholic religious order|Religious]] priests: 10\n*Religious sisters: 135\n*Religious Brothers: 9\n\n==Bishops==\nThe bishops of the diocese and their years of service:<ref name=chronology>[http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln \"Bishops of Lincoln\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319231857/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln |date=2015-03-19 }}  [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ Diocese of Lincoln.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319231857/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln Archived 2015-03-19] at [https://archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref>\n\n===Bishops of Lincoln===\n# [[Thomas Bonacum]] (1887-1911)\n# [[John Henry Tihen]] (1911-1917), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Bishop of Denver]]\n# [[Charles Joseph O'Reilly]] (1918-1923)\n# [[Francis Beckman]] (1924-1930), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archbishop of Dubuque]]\n# [[Louis Benedict Kucera]] (1930-1957)\n# [[James Vincent Casey]] (1957-1967), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archbishop of Denver]]\n# [[Glennon Patrick Flavin]] (1967-1992)\n# [[Fabian Bruskewitz]] (1992-2012)\n# [[James D. Conley]] (2012\u2013present)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n* [[Robert F. Vasa]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Baker|Bishop of Baker]] in 1999 and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Santa Rosa in California|Bishop of Santa Rosa in California]]\n* [[Thomas Olmsted]], appointed Coadjutor Bishop (in 1999) and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Wichita|Bishop of Wichita]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|Bishop of Phoenix]]\n* [[Michael Owen Jackels]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Wichita|Bishop of Wichita]] in 2005 and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archbishop of Dubuque]]\n* [[John Folda]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Fargo|Bishop of Fargo]] in 2013\n\n==High schools==\n*[[Aquinas High School (Nebraska)|Aquinas High School]], David City\n*[[Sacred Heart High School (Nebraska)|Sacred Heart High School]], Falls City\n*[[St. Cecilia High School (Nebraska)|St. Cecilia High School]], Hastings\n*[[Lourdes Central Catholic High School (Nebraska)|Lourdes Central Catholic High School]], Nebraska City\n*[[Pius X High School (Nebraska)|Pius X High School]], Lincoln\n*[[Bishop Neumann High School]], Wahoo\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|Lincoln (1)|Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Omaha|Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dioceseoflincoln.org/ Diocesan website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha}}\n{{coord|40|48|35|N|96|40|31|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln| ]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Lincoln]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1887]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century|Lincoln]]\n[[Category:1887 establishments in Nebraska]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the diocese of the Church of England|Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Lincoln\n| latin             = Dioecesis Lincolnensis\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska) from SE 1.JPG\n| image_size        = 250px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral of the Risen Christ\n| coat              = Coat of Arms of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln.svg\n| coat_size         = 175px \n| coat_alt          = \n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = [[United States]]\n| territory         = The territory that lies south of the [[Platte River]] across Southern Nebraska\n| province          = [[Archdiocese of Omaha|Omaha]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_sqmi         = 23,844<!-- Area in square miles, automatically converted -->\n| population        = 613,440\n| population_as_of  = 2017\n| catholics         = 97,027\n| catholics_percent = 15.8\n| parishes          = 134\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = 31\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church|Catholic]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = August 2, 1887 ({{age|1887|8|2}} years ago)\n| cathedral         = [[Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska)|Cathedral of the Risen Christ]]\n| cocathedral       = \n| patron            = [[Immaculate Conception]]\n| priests           = <!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop            = [[James D. Conley]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = [[Fabian Bruskewitz]]\n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Diocese of Lincoln map 1.png\n| map_alt           = \n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ www.lincolndiocese.org]<!-- [http://example.com example.com] --> \n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe '''Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Lincolnensis}}) is a [[Catholic Church|Catholic]] [[diocese]] in [[Nebraska]], [[United States]], and comprises the majority of the eastern and central portions of the state south of the [[Platte River]]. It is a [[suffragan see]] to the [[Archdiocese of Omaha]].  The [[episcopal see]] is in [[Lincoln, Nebraska]].  Bishop [[James D. Conley]] is the current ordinary of the Diocese. The [[Cathedral of the Risen Christ (Lincoln, Nebraska)|Cathedral of the Risen Christ]] is the [[cathedral]] [[parish]] of the diocese.\n \n==History==\n[[File:St. Mary's Catholic Church, Lincoln, Nebraska, USA.jpg|thumb|left|St. Mary's Church in Lincoln was the first cathedral]]\nThe diocese was established on August 2, 1887, by [[Pope Leo XIII]] from the territory taken from the [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Omaha|Diocese of Omaha]].<ref name=historylincoln>[http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese \"Brief History of the Diocese of Lincoln\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319225817/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese |date=2015-03-19 }}  [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ Catholic Diocese of Lincoln.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319225817/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/history-of-the-diocese Archived 2015-03-19] at [https://archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref><ref name=historyomaha>[http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ \"Archdiocese History\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214055440/http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ |date=2014-12-14 }}  [http://www.archomaha.org/ Archdiocese of Omaha.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20141214055440/http://www.archomaha.org/about/history/ Archived 2014-12-14] at [https://web.archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Bishop [[Fabian Bruskewitz]] issued a statement forbidding Catholics in the diocese to join a number of organizations, including the [[Society of St. Pius X]], [[Call to Action]], [[Planned Parenthood]], [[Catholics for a Free Choice]], the [[Hemlock Society]], and various [[Freemasonry|Masonic]] groups, under pain of excommunication.<ref name=excomm>Bruskewitz, Fabian.  [http://www.catholicculture.org/culture/library/view.cfm?recnum=2863 \"Statement of Bishop Bruskewitz Excommunicating Certain Groups\".]  Reproduced at [http://www.catholicculture.org/index.cfm CatholicCulture.org.]  1996-03-19.  Retrieved 2013-04-12.</ref>\n\nIn 2006, the Diocese rejected the proposed undertaking of an audit by the National Review Board of the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] - which would have examined whether the Diocese had effectively implemented national guidelines on [[sexual abuse|sex-abuse]] programs<ref name=\"ewers\">[http://www.cwnews.com/news/viewstory.cfm?recnum=43317 \"Bishop Bruskewitz shoots back at National Review Board\",]''Catholic World News'', April 2, 2006.</ref> In June 2014, the chairman of the U.S. Conference of Catholic Bishops' National Review Board for the protection of children reported that the Lincoln diocese was the only one in the United States that had yet to comply with the USCCB's charter requiring every diocese to submit its procedures for the protection of children to the Review Board for an audit.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Roewe|first1=Brian|title=Bishops talk sex abuse complacency, not accountability at annual meeting |url=http://ncronline.org/news/accountability/bishops-talk-sex-abuse-complacency-not-accountability-annual-meeting |accessdate=2015-05-04|work=National Catholic Reporter|date=2014-06-12}}</ref> According to a 2015 statement by Conley, the Lincoln Diocese has complied with all church and civil laws on child-abuse reporting and child protection. He stated that the audit process had been improved and that the diocese would now therefore participate.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jones |first=Kevin J |title=For Diocese of Lincoln, Audit Will Strengthen Its Effective Child-Protection |url=http://www.ncregister.com/daily-news/for-diocese-of-lincoln-audit-will-strengthen-its-effective-child-protection/ |date=September 11, 2015 |publisher=National Catholic Register |access-date=May 9, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe Diocese of Lincoln was the only diocese in the United States that does not allow female altar servers, after the only other holdout ended its prohibition on females in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |title=Neb. diocese is lone U.S. holdout on allowing altar girls |url=https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/religion/2006-03-22-altar-girls_x.htm |publisher=USA Today |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109074610/https://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/religion/2006-03-22-altar-girls_x.htm |archivedate=9 November 2017| url-status=live|date=22 March 2006|}}</ref> However, it was joined by a church in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|Diocese of Phoenix]] in August 2011, when it was announced that girls would no longer be allowed to altar serve.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Clancy |first1=Michael |title=Phoenix diocese cathedral won't allow girl altar servers |url=http://archive.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/local/articles/20110821phoenix-catholic-diocese-girl-servers.html#ixzz2HBvJANlK |website=The Arizona Republic |publisher=The Arizona Republic |accessdate=2 November 2018 |archiveurl=https://archive.fo/NA111 |archivedate=2 November 2018| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics and statistics<ref>{{cite web |title=Statistics |url=https://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/about-the-diocese/statistics |website=www.lincolndiocese.org}}</ref>==\n*Diocese patron: [[Immaculate Conception]]\n*Priests: 164\n*Deacons: 1 permanent; 2 transitional\n*Seminarians: 39\n*[[Catholic religious order|Religious]] priests: 10\n*Religious sisters: 135\n*Religious Brothers: 9\n\n==Bishops==\nThe bishops of the diocese and their years of service:<ref name=chronology>[http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln \"Bishops of Lincoln\".] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150319231857/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln |date=2015-03-19 }}  [http://www.lincolndiocese.org/ Diocese of Lincoln.]  Retrieved 2015-03-19.  [https://web.archive.org/web/20150319231857/http://www.lincolndiocese.org/diocese/bishops/bishops-of-lincoln Archived 2015-03-19] at [https://archive.org/web/ Wayback Machine].</ref>\n\n===Bishops of Lincoln===\n# [[Thomas Bonacum]] (1887-1911)\n# [[John Henry Tihen]] (1911-1917), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Bishop of Denver]]\n# [[Charles Joseph O'Reilly]] (1918-1923)\n# [[Francis Beckman]] (1924-1930), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archbishop of Dubuque]]\n# [[Louis Benedict Kucera]] (1930-1957)\n# [[James Vincent Casey]] (1957-1967), appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Denver|Archbishop of Denver]]\n# [[Glennon Patrick Flavin]] (1967-1992)\n# [[Fabian Bruskewitz]] (1992-2012)\n# [[James D. Conley]] (2012-present)\n\n===Other priests of this diocese who became bishops===\n* [[Robert F. Vasa]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Baker|Bishop of Baker]] in 1999 and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Santa Rosa in California|Bishop of Santa Rosa in California]]\n* [[Thomas Olmsted]], appointed Coadjutor Bishop (in 1999) and later [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Wichita|Bishop of Wichita]] and [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Phoenix|Bishop of Phoenix]]\n* [[Michael Owen Jackels]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Wichita|Bishop of Wichita]] in 2005 and later [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Dubuque|Archbishop of Dubuque]]\n* [[John Folda]], appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Fargo|Bishop of Fargo]] in 2013\n\n==High schools==\n*[[Aquinas High School (Nebraska)|Aquinas High School]], David City\n*[[Sacred Heart High School (Nebraska)|Sacred Heart High School]], Falls City\n*[[St. Cecilia High School (Nebraska)|St. Cecilia High School]], Hastings\n*[[Lourdes Central Catholic High School (Nebraska)|Lourdes Central Catholic High School]], Nebraska City\n*[[Pius X High School (Nebraska)|Pius X High School]], Lincoln\n*[[Bishop Neumann High School]], Wahoo\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikisource1913CatholicEnc|Lincoln (1)|Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Portal|Catholicism}}\n* [[Catholic Church by country]]\n* [[Catholic Church in the United States]]\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States#Ecclesiastical province of Omaha|Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha]]\n* [[Global organisation of the Catholic Church]]\n* [[List of Roman Catholic archdioceses]] (by country and continent)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (alphabetical)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of Roman Catholic dioceses (structured view)]] (including archdioceses)\n* [[List of the Catholic dioceses of the United States]]\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.dioceseoflincoln.org/ Diocesan website]\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha}}\n{{coord|40|48|35|N|96|40|31|W|source:plwiki|display=title}}\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Lincoln| ]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in the United States|Lincoln]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Omaha]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1887]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses and prelatures established in the 19th century|Lincoln]]\n[[Category:1887 establishmen